WEBVTT

00:00:16.060 --> 00:00:18.400
The Art of War by Tsuen Tzu.

00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:22.960
Part 1.

00:00:23.340 --> 00:00:25.400
Laying Plans.

00:00:25.400 --> 00:00:26.760
Tsuen Tzu said,

00:00:27.020 --> 00:00:30.140
The Art of War is of vital importance to the State.

00:00:31.160 --> 00:00:35.800
It is a matter of life and death, a road either to safety or to ruin.

00:00:36.620 --> 00:00:40.700
Hence it is a subject of inquiry, which can on no account be neglected.

00:00:41.740 --> 00:00:45.380
The Art of War, then, is governed by five constant factors,

00:00:45.960 --> 00:00:48.480
to be taken into account in one's deliberations,

00:00:48.900 --> 00:00:51.860
when seeking to determine the conditions obtaining in the field.

00:00:52.620 --> 00:00:53.820
These are,

00:00:54.120 --> 00:01:09.660
The moral law causes the people to be in complete accord with their ruler,

00:01:10.180 --> 00:01:12.760
so that they will follow him regardless of their lives,

00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:14.800
undismayed by any danger.

00:01:15.640 --> 00:01:21.280
Heaven signifies night and day, cold and heat, times and seasons.

00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:27.420
Earth comprises distances, great and small, danger and security,

00:01:28.020 --> 00:01:32.120
open ground and narrow passes, the chances of life and death.

00:01:33.400 --> 00:01:39.900
The commander stands for the virtues of wisdom, sincerity, benevolence, courage and strictness.

00:01:40.660 --> 00:01:46.240
By method and discipline are to be understood the marshalling of the army in its proper subdivisions,

00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:48.920
the graduations of rank among the officers,

00:01:49.560 --> 00:01:52.920
the maintenance of roads by which supplies may reach the army,

00:01:53.200 --> 00:01:55.180
and the control of military expenditure.

00:01:56.360 --> 00:01:59.060
These five heads should be familiar to every general.

00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:04.240
He who knows them will be victorious, he who knows them not will fail.

00:02:05.460 --> 00:02:09.820
Therefore, in your deliberations, when seeking to determine the military conditions,

00:02:10.440 --> 00:02:13.620
let them be made the basis of a comparison in this wise.

00:02:35.660 --> 00:02:39.580
Six, on which side are officers and men more highly trained?

00:02:40.340 --> 00:02:45.190
Seven, in which army is there the greater constancy, both in reward and punishment?

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:51.460
By means of these seven considerations, I can forecast victory or defeat.

00:02:52.480 --> 00:02:56.000
The general that hearkens to my counsel and acts upon it will conquer.

00:02:56.640 --> 00:02:58.880
Let such a one be retained in command.

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:04.220
The general that hearkens not to my counsel nor acts upon it will suffer defeat.

00:03:04.220 --> 00:03:06.400
Let such a one be dismissed.

00:03:07.540 --> 00:03:12.260
While heeding the profit of my counsel, avail yourself also of any helpful circumstances

00:03:12.260 --> 00:03:14.320
over and beyond the ordinary rules.

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:18.980
According as circumstances are favorable, one should modify one's plans.

00:03:20.220 --> 00:03:22.420
All warfare is based on deception.

00:03:23.200 --> 00:03:26.600
Hence, when able to attack, we must seem unable.

00:03:27.160 --> 00:03:30.000
When using our forces, we must seem inactive.

00:03:30.510 --> 00:03:34.300
When we are near, we must make the enemy believe we are far away.

00:03:34.820 --> 00:03:37.600
When far away, we must make him believe we are near.

00:03:38.540 --> 00:03:40.840
Hold out baits to entice the enemy.

00:03:41.460 --> 00:03:43.420
Fain disorder and crush him.

00:03:44.340 --> 00:03:47.080
If he is secure at all points, be prepared for him.

00:03:47.680 --> 00:03:50.420
If he is in superior strength, evade him.

00:03:51.300 --> 00:03:55.340
If your opponent is of choleric temper, seek to irritate him.

00:03:55.540 --> 00:03:57.860
Pretend to be weak, that he may grow arrogant.

00:03:58.560 --> 00:04:01.380
If he is taking his ease, give him no rest.

00:04:02.020 --> 00:04:05.040
If his forces are united, separate them.

00:04:05.720 --> 00:04:07.680
Attack him where he is unprepared.

00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:10.200
Appear where you are not expected.

00:04:11.580 --> 00:04:16.700
These military devices, leading to victory, must not be divulged beforehand.

00:04:18.140 --> 00:04:21.980
Now the general who wins a battle makes many calculations in his temple

00:04:21.980 --> 00:04:23.220
ere the battle is fought.

00:04:23.740 --> 00:04:27.940
The general who loses a battle makes but few calculations beforehand.

00:04:28.760 --> 00:04:33.480
Thus do many calculations lead to victory and few calculations to defeat.

00:04:34.120 --> 00:04:36.280
How much more, no calculation at all?

00:04:37.020 --> 00:04:41.920
It is by attention to this point that I can foresee who is likely to win or lose.

00:04:49.260 --> 00:04:52.100
Sun Tzu said, in the operations of war,

00:04:52.100 --> 00:04:56.680
where there are in the field a thousand swift chariots, as many heavy chariots,

00:04:56.760 --> 00:05:01.540
and a hundred thousand male-clad soldiers, with provisions enough to carry them a thousand li,

00:05:02.020 --> 00:05:05.880
the expenditure at home and at the front, including entertainment of guests,

00:05:06.420 --> 00:05:10.800
small items such as glue and paint, and some spent on chariots and armor,

00:05:11.180 --> 00:05:14.320
will reach the total of a thousand ounces of silver per day,

00:05:14.840 --> 00:05:17.940
such as the cost of raising an army of a hundred thousand men.

00:05:18.980 --> 00:05:22.660
When you engage in actual fighting, if victory is long in coming,

00:05:22.920 --> 00:05:25.820
then men's weapons will grow dull and their ardor will be damped.

00:05:26.560 --> 00:05:29.700
If you lay siege to a town, you will exhaust your strength.

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:35.740
Again, if the campaign is protracted, the resources of the state will not be equal to the strain.

00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:41.020
Now, when your weapons are dulled, your ardor damped, your strength exhausted,

00:05:41.140 --> 00:05:46.080
and your treasure spent, other chieftains will spring up to take advantage of your extremity.

00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:51.680
Then no man, however wise, will be able to avert the consequences that must ensue.

00:05:52.800 --> 00:05:58.320
Thus, though we have heard of stupid haste in war, cleverness has never been seen associated

00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:04.140
with long delays. There is no instance of a country having benefited from prolonged warfare.

00:06:04.960 --> 00:06:08.220
It is only one who is thoroughly acquainted with the evils of war

00:06:08.220 --> 00:06:11.800
that can thoroughly understand the profitable way of carrying it on.

00:06:12.600 --> 00:06:15.420
The skillful soldier does not raise a second levy.

00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:19.100
Neither are his supply wagons loaded more than twice.

00:06:20.080 --> 00:06:23.500
Bring war material with you from home, but forage on the enemy.

00:06:24.040 --> 00:06:26.460
Thus the army will have food enough for its needs.

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:32.640
Poverty of the state exchequer causes an army to be maintained by contributions from a distance.

00:06:33.380 --> 00:06:37.340
Contributing to maintain an army at a distance causes the people to be impoverished.

00:06:37.900 --> 00:06:41.620
On the other hand, the proximity of an army causes prices to go up,

00:06:41.960 --> 00:06:45.240
and high prices cause the people's substance to be drained away.

00:06:46.620 --> 00:06:51.280
When their substance is drained away, the peasantry will be afflicted by heavy exactions.

00:06:51.980 --> 00:06:56.720
With this loss of substance and exhaustion of strength, the homes of the people will be stripped

00:06:56.720 --> 00:07:02.180
bare, and three-tenths of their income will be dissipated, while government expenses for broken

00:07:02.180 --> 00:07:07.540
chariots, worn-out horses, breastplates and helmets, bows and arrows, spears and shields,

00:07:08.140 --> 00:07:13.740
protective mantles, draught oxen, and heavy wagons will amount to four-tenths of its total revenue.

00:07:15.200 --> 00:07:18.280
Hence a wise general makes a point of foraging on the enemy.

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:22.800
One cartload of the enemy's provisions is equivalent to twenty of one's own,

00:07:23.360 --> 00:07:28.440
and likewise a single pickle of his provender is equivalent to twenty from one's own store.

00:07:29.520 --> 00:07:32.780
Now, in order to kill the enemy, our men must be roused to anger.

00:07:33.360 --> 00:07:37.460
But there may be advantage from defeating the enemy, they must have their rewards.

00:07:38.360 --> 00:07:41.840
Therefore, in chariot fighting, when ten or more chariots have been taken,

00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:44.140
those should be rewarded who took the first.

00:07:44.680 --> 00:07:47.520
Our own flags should be substituted for those of the enemy,

00:07:47.960 --> 00:07:51.040
and their chariots mingled and used in conjunction with ours.

00:07:51.740 --> 00:07:54.560
The captured soldiers should be kindly treated and kept.

00:07:55.310 --> 00:07:59.220
This is called using the conquered foe to augment one's own strength.

00:08:00.280 --> 00:08:04.180
In war, then, let your great object be victory, not lengthy campaigns.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:08.800
Thus it may be known that the leader of armies is the arbiter of the people's fate,

00:08:09.360 --> 00:08:13.460
the man on whom it depends whether the nation shall be in peace or in peril.

00:08:36.580 --> 00:08:37.900
III.

00:08:38.560 --> 00:08:40.060
ATTACK BY STRATEGYM

00:08:41.060 --> 00:08:42.200
Sun Tzu said,

00:08:42.520 --> 00:09:00.360
In the practical art of war, the best thing of all is to take the enemy's country whole and intact. To shatter and destroy it is not so good. So too it is better to recapture an army entire than to destroy it, to capture a regiment, a detachment, or a company entire than to destroy them.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:10.140
Hence to fight and conquer in all your battles is not supreme excellence. Supreme excellence consists in breaking the enemy's resistance without fighting.

00:09:11.240 --> 00:09:26.080
Thus the highest form of generalship is to balk the enemy's plans. The next best is to prevent the junction of the enemy's forces. The next in order is to attack the enemy's army in the field. And the worst policy of all is to besiege walled cities.

00:09:26.920 --> 00:09:41.800
The rule is not to besiege walled cities if it can possibly be avoided. The preparation of mantlets, movable shelters, and various implements of war will take up three whole months, and the piling up of mounds against the walls will take three months more.

00:09:42.420 --> 00:09:57.320
The general, unable to control his irritation, will launch his men to the assault like swarming ants, with the result that one third of his men are slain, while the town still remains untaken. Such are the disastrous effects of a siege.

00:09:58.520 --> 00:10:09.240
Therefore the skillful leader subdues the enemy's troops without any fighting. He captures their cities without laying siege to them. He overthrows their kingdom without lengthy operations in the field.

00:10:09.860 --> 00:10:20.520
With his forces intact, he will dispute the mastery of the empire, and thus, without losing a man, his triumph will be complete. This is the method of attacking by stratagem.

00:10:21.260 --> 00:10:41.780
It is the rule in war if our forces are ten to the enemy's one, to surround him, if five to one, to attack him, if twice as numerous, to divide our army into two. If equally matched, we can offer battle. If slightly inferior in numbers, we can avoid the enemy. If quite unequal in every way, we can flee from him.

00:10:42.520 --> 00:10:49.440
Hence, though an obstinate fight may be made by a small force, in the end it must be captured by the larger force.

00:10:50.400 --> 00:10:59.540
Now the general is the bulwark of the state. If the bulwark is complete at all points, the state will be strong. If the bulwark is defective, the state will be weak.

00:10:59.540 --> 00:11:03.840
There are three ways in which a ruler can bring misfortune upon his army.

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:12.560
One, by commanding the army to advance or to retreat, being ignorant of the fact that it cannot obey. This is called hobbling the army.

00:11:13.400 --> 00:11:24.100
Two, by attempting to govern an army in the same way as he administers a kingdom, being ignorant of the conditions which obtain in an army. This causes restlessness in the soldier's minds.

00:11:24.980 --> 00:11:36.220
Three, by employing the officers of his army without discrimination through ignorance of the military principle of adaptation to circumstances. This shakes the confidence of the soldiers.

00:11:37.380 --> 00:11:46.660
But when the army is restless and distrustful, trouble is sure to come from the other feudal princes. This is simply bringing anarchy into the army and flinging victory away.

00:11:47.540 --> 00:11:51.040
Thus we may know that there are five essentials for victory.

00:11:51.740 --> 00:11:56.360
One, he will win who knows when to fight and when not to fight.

00:11:56.900 --> 00:12:01.840
Two, he will win who knows how to handle both superior and inferior forces.

00:12:02.820 --> 00:12:07.720
Three, he will win whose army is animated by the same spirit throughout all its ranks.

00:12:08.700 --> 00:12:13.840
Four, he will win who, prepared himself, waits to take the enemy unprepared.

00:12:14.580 --> 00:12:20.520
Five, he will win who has military capacity and is not interfered with by the sovereign.

00:12:21.940 --> 00:12:28.100
Hence the saying, if you know the enemy and know yourself, you need not fear the result of a hundred battles.

00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:34.120
If you know yourself but not the enemy, for every victory gained you will also suffer a defeat.

00:12:34.760 --> 00:12:39.360
If you know neither the enemy nor yourself, you will succumb in every battle.

00:12:40.120 --> 00:12:43.060
End of part three.

00:12:44.040 --> 00:12:46.940
Part four. Tactical dispositions.

00:12:48.180 --> 00:12:56.120
Sun Tzu said, the good fighters of old first put themselves beyond the possibility of defeat and then waited for an opportunity of defeating the enemy.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:04.800
To secure ourselves against defeat lies in our own hands, but the opportunity of defeating the enemy is provided by the enemy himself.

00:13:04.800 --> 00:13:11.420
Thus the good fighter is able to secure himself against defeat but cannot make certain of defeating the enemy.

00:13:12.180 --> 00:13:16.880
Hence the saying, one may know how to conquer without being able to do it.

00:13:17.800 --> 00:13:20.580
Security against defeat implies defensive tactics.

00:13:21.140 --> 00:13:23.840
Ability to defeat the enemy means taking the offensive.

00:13:24.880 --> 00:13:30.820
Standing on the defensive indicates insufficient strength, attacking a superabundance of strength.

00:13:31.740 --> 00:13:36.360
The general who is skilled in defense hides in the most secret recesses of the earth.

00:13:36.900 --> 00:13:41.100
He who is skilled and attacked flashes forth from the topmost heights of heaven.

00:13:42.160 --> 00:13:47.600
Thus on the one hand we have ability to protect ourselves, on the other a victory that is complete.

00:13:48.680 --> 00:13:54.120
To see victory only when it is within the ken of the common herd is not the acme of excellence.

00:13:54.120 --> 00:14:00.760
Neither is it the acme of excellence if you fight and conquer and the whole empire says, well done.

00:14:02.160 --> 00:14:05.300
To lift an autumn hare is no sign of great strength.

00:14:05.900 --> 00:14:08.720
To see the sun and moon is no sign of sharp sight.

00:14:09.680 --> 00:14:12.840
To hear the noise of thunder is no sign of a quick ear.

00:14:13.720 --> 00:14:19.780
What the ancients called a clever fighter is one who not only wins but excels in winning with ease.

00:14:19.780 --> 00:14:25.340
Hence his victories bring him neither reputation for wisdom nor credit for courage.

00:14:26.460 --> 00:14:29.040
He wins his battles by making no mistakes.

00:14:29.740 --> 00:14:36.240
Making no mistakes is what establishes the certainty of victory, for it means conquering an enemy that is already defeated.

00:14:37.020 --> 00:14:44.680
Hence the skillful fighter puts himself into a position which makes defeat impossible and does not miss the moment for defeating the enemy.

00:14:45.520 --> 00:14:51.240
Thus it is that in war the victorious strategist only seeks battle after the victory has been won,

00:14:51.520 --> 00:14:56.300
whereas he who is destined to defeat first fights and afterwards looks for victory.

00:14:57.960 --> 00:15:03.080
The consummate leader cultivates the moral law and strictly adheres to method and discipline.

00:15:03.760 --> 00:15:06.300
Thus it is in his power to control success.

00:15:07.080 --> 00:15:19.820
In respect of military method we have firstly measurement, secondly estimation of quantity, thirdly calculation, fourthly balancing of chances, fifthly victory.

00:15:20.900 --> 00:15:22.960
Measurement owes its existence to earth.

00:15:23.640 --> 00:15:32.260
Estimation of quantity to measurement, calculation to estimation of quantity, balancing of chances to calculation, and victory to balancing of chances.

00:15:32.260 --> 00:15:39.260
A victorious army opposed to a routed one is as a pound's weight placed in the scale against a single grain.

00:15:40.460 --> 00:15:47.040
The onrush of a conquering force is like the bursting of pent-up waters into a chasm a thousand fathoms deep.

00:16:04.280 --> 00:16:06.500
The Art of War by Sun Tzu.

00:16:09.360 --> 00:16:11.160
Part V. Energy.

00:16:12.640 --> 00:16:17.280
Sun Tzu said, The control of a large force is the same principle as the control of a

00:16:17.280 --> 00:16:17.820
few men.

00:16:17.820 --> 00:16:20.860
It is merely a question of dividing up their numbers.

00:16:21.860 --> 00:16:25.720
Fighting with a large army under your command is no wise different from fighting with a

00:16:25.720 --> 00:16:26.300
small one.

00:16:26.780 --> 00:16:29.980
It is merely a question of instituting signs and signals.

00:16:31.040 --> 00:16:35.260
To ensure that your whole host may withstand the brunt of the enemy's attack and remain

00:16:35.260 --> 00:16:39.380
unshaken, this is affected by maneuvers direct and indirect.

00:16:40.460 --> 00:16:45.800
That the impact of your army may be like a grindstone dashed against an egg, this is

00:16:45.800 --> 00:16:48.320
affected by the science of weak points and strong.

00:16:49.580 --> 00:16:54.440
In all fighting, the direct method may be used for joining battle, but indirect methods

00:16:54.440 --> 00:16:56.600
will be needed in order to secure victory.

00:16:57.660 --> 00:17:03.380
Indirect tactics, efficiently applied, are inexhaustible as heaven and earth, unending

00:17:03.380 --> 00:17:05.160
as the flow of rivers and streams.

00:17:05.560 --> 00:17:08.340
Like the sun and moon, they end but to begin anew.

00:17:08.600 --> 00:17:12.560
Like the four seasons, they pass away to return once more.

00:17:13.240 --> 00:17:18.480
There are not more than five musical notes, yet the combinations of these five give rise

00:17:18.480 --> 00:17:20.480
to more melodies than can ever be heard.

00:17:21.400 --> 00:17:27.660
There are not more than five primary colors—blue, yellow, red, white, and black—yet in combination

00:17:27.660 --> 00:17:30.120
they produce more hues than can ever be seen.

00:17:31.020 --> 00:17:37.500
There are not more than five cardinal tastes—sour, acrid, salt, sweet, bitter—yet combinations

00:17:37.500 --> 00:17:40.140
of them yield more flavors than can ever be tasted.

00:17:40.900 --> 00:17:47.000
In battle, there are not more than two methods of attack, the direct and the indirect, yet

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:50.960
these two in combination give rise to an endless series of maneuvers.

00:17:52.140 --> 00:17:55.220
The direct and the indirect lead on to each other in turn.

00:17:55.860 --> 00:17:59.000
It is like moving in a circle—you never come to an end.

00:17:59.540 --> 00:18:02.100
Who can exhaust the possibilities of their combination?

00:18:03.020 --> 00:18:07.460
The onset of troops is like the rush of a torrent which will even roll stones along

00:18:07.460 --> 00:18:08.280
in its course.

00:18:09.060 --> 00:18:14.160
The quality of decision is like the well-timed swoop of a falcon which enables it to strike

00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:15.460
and destroy its victim.

00:18:16.580 --> 00:18:21.440
Therefore, the good fighter will be terrible in his onset and prompt in his decision.

00:18:22.760 --> 00:18:27.640
Energy may be likened to the bending of a crossbow, decision to the releasing of a trigger.

00:18:28.380 --> 00:18:33.800
Amid the turmoil and tumult of battle, there may be seeming disorder, and yet no real disorder

00:18:33.800 --> 00:18:34.500
at all.

00:18:34.500 --> 00:18:40.560
Amid confusion and chaos, your array may be without head or tail, yet it will be proof

00:18:40.560 --> 00:18:41.460
against defeat.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:45.820
Simulated disorder postulates perfect discipline.

00:18:46.400 --> 00:18:48.480
Simulated fear postulates courage.

00:18:49.020 --> 00:18:51.620
Simulated weakness postulates strength.

00:18:53.100 --> 00:18:57.140
Hiding order beneath the cloak of disorder is simply a question of subdivision.

00:18:57.560 --> 00:19:02.680
Concealing courage under their show of timidity presupposes a fund of latent energy.

00:19:03.240 --> 00:19:07.480
Masking strength with weakness is to be affected by tactical dispositions.

00:19:08.380 --> 00:19:13.700
Thus, one who is skillful at keeping the enemy on the move maintains deceitful appearances

00:19:13.700 --> 00:19:16.160
according to which the enemy will act.

00:19:16.560 --> 00:19:20.200
He sacrifices something that the enemy may snatch at it.

00:19:20.780 --> 00:19:26.240
By holding out baits he keeps him on the march, then with a body of picked men he lies in

00:19:26.240 --> 00:19:26.920
wait for him.

00:19:27.480 --> 00:19:32.860
The clever combatant looks to the effect of combined energy and does not require too much

00:19:32.860 --> 00:19:38.240
from individuals, hence his ability to pick out the right men and utilize combined energy.

00:19:39.280 --> 00:19:44.620
When he utilizes combined energy, his fighting men become as it were like unto rolling logs

00:19:44.620 --> 00:19:49.560
or stones, for it is the nature of a log or stone to remain motionless on level ground

00:19:49.560 --> 00:19:55.820
and to move when on a slope, if four-cornered to come to a standstill, but if round shaped

00:19:55.820 --> 00:19:57.540
to go rolling down.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:02.940
Thus the energy developed by good fighting men is as the momentum of a round stone rolled

00:20:02.940 --> 00:20:05.260
down a mountain thousands of feet in height.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.140
So much on the subject of energy.

00:20:09.300 --> 00:20:12.520
End of part five.

00:20:13.360 --> 00:20:14.100
Part six.

00:20:14.260 --> 00:20:15.920
Weak points and strong.

00:20:17.420 --> 00:20:22.260
Sun Tzu said, whoever is first in the field and awaits the coming of the enemy will be

00:20:22.260 --> 00:20:23.300
fresh for the fight.

00:20:23.860 --> 00:20:28.220
Whoever is second in the field and has to hasten to battle will arrive exhausted.

00:20:29.360 --> 00:20:34.160
Therefore, the clever combatant imposes his will on the enemy, but does not allow the

00:20:34.160 --> 00:20:36.220
enemy's will to be imposed on him.

00:20:37.280 --> 00:20:42.840
By holding out advantages to him, he can cause the enemy to approach of his own accord, or

00:20:42.840 --> 00:20:47.000
by inflicting damage, he can make it impossible for the enemy to draw near.

00:20:48.020 --> 00:20:51.040
If the enemy is taking his ease, he can harass him.

00:20:51.040 --> 00:20:54.020
If well supplied with food, he can starve him out.

00:20:54.420 --> 00:20:57.400
If quietly encamped, he can force him to move.

00:20:58.660 --> 00:21:01.220
Appear at points which the enemy must hasten to defend.

00:21:01.700 --> 00:21:04.280
March swiftly to places where you are not expected.

00:21:05.380 --> 00:21:09.980
An army may march great distances without distress if it marches through country where

00:21:09.980 --> 00:21:11.060
the enemy is not.

00:21:12.300 --> 00:21:16.840
You can be sure of succeeding in your attacks if you only attack places which are undefended.

00:21:17.400 --> 00:21:21.940
You can ensure the safety of your defense if you only hold positions that cannot be

00:21:21.940 --> 00:21:22.540
attacked.

00:21:23.760 --> 00:21:28.320
Hence the general is skillful in attack whose opponent does not know what to defend, and

00:21:28.320 --> 00:21:32.000
he is skillful in defense whose opponent does not know what to attack.

00:21:32.980 --> 00:21:38.580
O divine art of subtlety and secrecy, through you we learn to be invisible, through you

00:21:38.580 --> 00:21:42.420
inaudible, and hence we can hold the enemy's fate in our hands.

00:21:43.540 --> 00:21:48.960
You may advance and be absolutely irresistible if you make for the enemy's weak points.

00:21:49.640 --> 00:21:54.040
You may retire and be safe from pursuit if your movements are more rapid than those of

00:21:54.040 --> 00:21:54.460
the enemy.

00:21:55.480 --> 00:22:00.180
If we wish to fight, the enemy can be forced to an engagement even though he be sheltered

00:22:00.180 --> 00:22:02.280
behind a high rampart and a deep ditch.

00:22:03.220 --> 00:22:07.280
All we need do is attack some other place that he will be obliged to relieve.

00:22:08.140 --> 00:22:13.080
If we do not wish to fight, we can prevent the enemy from engaging us even though the

00:22:13.080 --> 00:22:15.920
lines of our encampment be merely traced out on the ground.

00:22:16.720 --> 00:22:21.140
All we need do is throw something odd and unaccountable in his way.

00:22:22.380 --> 00:22:27.040
By discovering the enemy's dispositions and remaining invisible ourselves, we can keep

00:22:27.040 --> 00:22:30.100
our forces concentrated while the enemy's must be divided.

00:22:30.920 --> 00:22:35.280
We can form a single united body while the enemy must split up into fractions.

00:22:35.840 --> 00:22:40.340
Hence there will be a whole pitted against separate parts of a whole, which means that

00:22:40.340 --> 00:22:42.420
we shall be many to the enemy's few.

00:22:43.680 --> 00:22:48.720
And if we are able thus to attack an inferior force with a superior one, our opponents will

00:22:48.720 --> 00:22:50.200
be in dire straits.

00:22:51.220 --> 00:22:55.740
The spot where we intend to fight must not be made known, for then the enemy will have

00:22:55.740 --> 00:22:58.620
to prepare against a possible attack at several different points.

00:22:59.420 --> 00:23:03.940
And his forces being thus distributed in many directions, the numbers we shall have to face

00:23:03.940 --> 00:23:06.400
at any given point will be proportionately few.

00:23:07.280 --> 00:23:11.020
For should the enemy strengthen his van, he will weaken his rear.

00:23:11.500 --> 00:23:13.940
Should he strengthen his rear, he will weaken his van.

00:23:14.520 --> 00:23:17.140
Should he strengthen his left, he will weaken his right.

00:23:17.560 --> 00:23:20.240
Should he strengthen his right, he will weaken his left.

00:23:20.880 --> 00:23:24.700
If he sends reinforcements everywhere, he will everywhere be weak.

00:23:26.300 --> 00:23:29.820
Numerical weakness comes from having to prepare against possible attacks.

00:23:30.600 --> 00:23:36.120
Numerical strength from compelling our adversary to make these preparations against us.

00:23:36.360 --> 00:23:40.620
Knowing the place and the time of the coming battle, we may concentrate from the greatest

00:23:40.620 --> 00:23:42.180
distances in order to fight.

00:23:42.840 --> 00:23:47.360
But if neither time nor place be known, then the left wing will be impotent to secure the

00:23:47.360 --> 00:23:52.840
right, the right equally impotent to secure the left, the van unable to relieve the rear

00:23:52.840 --> 00:23:54.400
or the rear to support the van.

00:23:55.080 --> 00:23:59.520
How much more so if the furtherest proportions of the army are anything under a hundred li

00:23:59.520 --> 00:24:02.780
apart, and even the nearest are separated by several li?

00:24:04.520 --> 00:24:09.260
Though according to my estimate the soldiers of Yue exceed our own in number, that shall

00:24:09.260 --> 00:24:11.400
advantage them nothing in the matter of victory.

00:24:11.900 --> 00:24:13.980
I say then that victory can be achieved.

00:24:14.700 --> 00:24:18.420
Though the enemy be stronger in numbers, we may prevent him from fighting.

00:24:19.100 --> 00:24:23.000
Scheme so as to discover his plans and the likelihood of their success.

00:24:23.660 --> 00:24:27.300
Rouse him and learn the principle of his activity or inactivity.

00:24:27.980 --> 00:24:31.860
Force him to reveal himself so as to find out his vulnerable spots.

00:24:32.620 --> 00:24:36.960
Carefully compare the opposing army with your own, so that you may know where strength is

00:24:36.960 --> 00:24:39.040
superabundant and where it is deficient.

00:24:40.120 --> 00:24:44.660
In making tactical dispositions, the highest pitch you can attain is to conceal them.

00:24:45.140 --> 00:24:49.060
Conceal your dispositions and you will be safe from the prying of the subtlest spies

00:24:49.060 --> 00:24:51.800
from the machinations of the wisest brains.

00:24:53.580 --> 00:24:58.640
How victory may be produced for them out of the enemy's own tactics, that is what the

00:24:58.640 --> 00:25:00.060
multitude cannot comprehend.

00:25:01.200 --> 00:25:06.800
All men can see the tactics whereby I conquer, but what none can see is the strategy out

00:25:06.800 --> 00:25:08.340
of which victory is evolved.

00:25:09.480 --> 00:25:14.200
Do not repeat the tactics which have gained you one victory, but let your methods be regulated

00:25:14.200 --> 00:25:16.580
by the infinite variety of circumstances.

00:25:17.760 --> 00:25:22.620
Military tactics are like unto water, for water in its natural course runs away from

00:25:22.620 --> 00:25:24.480
high places and hastens downwards.

00:25:25.320 --> 00:25:29.800
So in war, the way is to avoid what is strong and to strike at what is weak.

00:25:30.440 --> 00:25:34.480
Water shapes its course according to the nature of the ground over which it flows.

00:25:35.180 --> 00:25:39.040
The soldier works out his victory in relation to the foe whom he is facing.

00:25:39.820 --> 00:25:46.560
Therefore, just as water retains no constant shape, in warfare there are no constant conditions

00:25:47.440 --> 00:25:52.480
He who can modify his tactics in relation to his opponent and thereby succeed in winning

00:25:52.480 --> 00:25:54.820
may be called a heaven-born captain.

00:25:56.060 --> 00:26:02.240
The five elements, water, fire, wood, metal, earth, are not always equally predominant.

00:26:02.660 --> 00:26:05.020
The four seasons make way for each other in turn.

00:26:05.500 --> 00:26:07.060
There are short days and long.

00:26:07.580 --> 00:26:11.420
The moon has its periods of waning and waxing.

00:26:12.420 --> 00:26:14.600
End of part 6

00:26:14.600 --> 00:26:20.300
Recorded in Toronto, Ontario by Moira Fogarty, October 2006

00:26:44.260 --> 00:26:47.640
PART VII MANEUVERING

00:26:47.640 --> 00:26:49.120
Sun Tzu said,

00:27:27.740 --> 00:27:33.540
Maneuvering with an army is advantageous, with an undisciplined multitude most dangerous.

00:27:34.780 --> 00:27:39.500
If you set a fully equipped army in march in order to snatch an advantage, the chances

00:27:39.500 --> 00:27:41.280
are that you will be too late.

00:27:41.740 --> 00:27:46.720
On the other hand, to detach a flying column for the purpose involves the sacrifice of

00:27:48.620 --> 00:27:53.700
Thus, if you order your men to roll up their buffcoats and make forced marches without

00:27:53.700 --> 00:27:58.420
halting day or night, covering double the usual distance at a stretch, doing a hundred

00:27:58.420 --> 00:28:03.560
li in order to wrest an advantage, the leaders of all your three divisions will fall into

00:28:03.560 --> 00:28:04.660
the hands of the enemy.

00:28:05.740 --> 00:28:11.400
The stronger men will be in front, the jaded ones will fall behind, and on this plan only

00:28:11.400 --> 00:28:13.980
one tenth of your army will reach its destination.

00:28:14.840 --> 00:28:20.340
If you march fifty li in order to outmaneuver the enemy, you will lose the leader of your

00:28:20.340 --> 00:28:23.180
first division and only half your force will reach the goal.

00:28:23.920 --> 00:28:28.420
If you march thirty li with the same object, two thirds of your army will arrive.

00:28:29.500 --> 00:28:33.020
We may take it then that an army without its baggage train is lost.

00:28:33.260 --> 00:28:35.060
Without provisions, it is lost.

00:28:35.440 --> 00:28:38.060
Without bases of supply, it is lost.

00:28:38.740 --> 00:28:43.600
We cannot enter into alliances until we are acquainted with the designs of our neighbors.

00:28:45.280 --> 00:28:49.200
We are not fit to lead an army on the march unless we are familiar with the face of the

00:28:49.200 --> 00:28:55.200
country, its mountains and forests, its pitfalls and precipices, its marshes and swamps.

00:28:56.140 --> 00:29:01.580
We shall be unable to turn natural advantage to account unless we make use of local guides.

00:29:02.520 --> 00:29:05.780
In war, practice dissimulation and you will succeed.

00:29:06.300 --> 00:29:10.980
Whether to concentrate or to divide your troops must be decided by circumstances.

00:29:12.080 --> 00:29:16.280
Let your rapidity be that of the wind, your compactness that of the forest.

00:29:16.940 --> 00:29:21.500
In raiding and plundering be like fire, in immovability like a mountain.

00:29:22.620 --> 00:29:29.040
Let your plans be dark and impenetrable as night and when you move, fall like a thunderbolt.

00:29:29.860 --> 00:29:33.640
When you plunder a countryside, let the spoil be divided amongst your men.

00:29:34.060 --> 00:29:39.740
When you capture new territory, cut it up into allotments for the benefit of the soldiery.

00:29:39.900 --> 00:29:42.520
Ponder and deliberate before you make a move.

00:29:43.500 --> 00:29:49.200
He will conquer who has learnt the artifice of deviation, such as the art of maneuvering.

00:29:49.960 --> 00:29:55.460
The Book of Army Management says, On the field of battle the spoken word does not carry far

00:29:55.460 --> 00:30:01.620
enough, hence the institution of gongs and drums, nor can ordinary objects be seen clearly

00:30:01.620 --> 00:30:04.740
enough, hence the institution of banners and flags.

00:30:05.740 --> 00:30:11.660
Gongs and drums, banners and flags are means whereby the ears and eyes of the host may

00:30:11.660 --> 00:30:13.820
be focused on one particular point.

00:30:14.960 --> 00:30:20.540
The host thus forming a single united body, it is impossible either for the brave to advance

00:30:20.540 --> 00:30:23.480
alone or for the cowardly to retreat alone.

00:30:24.180 --> 00:30:27.040
This is the art of handling large masses of men.

00:30:27.920 --> 00:30:33.440
In night fighting, then, make much use of signal flyers and drums, and in fighting by

00:30:33.440 --> 00:30:38.280
day of flags and banners, as a means of influencing the ears and eyes of your army.

00:30:39.180 --> 00:30:44.120
A whole army may be robbed of its spirit, a commander-in-chief may be robbed of his

00:30:44.120 --> 00:30:45.000
presence of mind.

00:30:46.380 --> 00:30:50.900
Now a soldier's spirit is keenest in the morning, by noonday it has begun to flag,

00:30:51.300 --> 00:30:54.380
and in the evening his mind is bent only on returning to camp.

00:30:55.200 --> 00:31:00.320
A clever general, therefore, avoids an army when its spirit is keen, but attacks it when

00:31:00.320 --> 00:31:02.160
it is sluggish and inclined to return.

00:31:02.760 --> 00:31:06.140
This is the art of studying moods.

00:31:06.240 --> 00:31:10.380
Disciplined and calm to await the appearance of disorder and hubbub amongst the enemy,

00:31:10.940 --> 00:31:13.560
this is the art of retaining self-possession.

00:31:14.500 --> 00:31:20.040
To be near the goal while the enemy is still far from it, to wait at ease while the enemy

00:31:20.040 --> 00:31:25.600
is toiling and struggling, to be well fed while the enemy is famished, this is the art

00:31:25.600 --> 00:31:27.180
of husbanding one's strength.

00:31:28.320 --> 00:31:33.720
To refrain from intercepting an enemy whose banners are in perfect order, to refrain from

00:31:33.720 --> 00:31:39.880
attacking an army drawn up in calm and confident array, this is the art of studying circumstances.

00:31:40.780 --> 00:31:46.160
It is a military axiom not to advance uphill against the enemy, nor to oppose him when

00:31:46.160 --> 00:31:47.160
he comes downhill.

00:31:47.800 --> 00:31:50.520
Do not pursue an enemy who simulates flight.

00:31:51.100 --> 00:31:53.660
Do not attack soldiers whose temper is keen.

00:31:54.640 --> 00:31:56.740
Do not swallow bait offered by the enemy.

00:31:57.240 --> 00:32:00.280
Do not interfere with an army that is returning home.

00:32:01.180 --> 00:32:04.120
When you surround an army, leave an outlet free.

00:32:04.840 --> 00:32:07.180
Do not press a desperate foe too hard.

00:32:07.680 --> 00:32:09.700
Such is the art of warfare.

00:32:10.980 --> 00:32:13.160
End of part 7.

00:32:14.460 --> 00:32:15.640
Part 8.

00:32:16.040 --> 00:32:17.500
Variation in tactics.

00:32:18.520 --> 00:32:23.680
Sun Tzu said, In war, the general receives his commands from the sovereign, collects

00:32:23.680 --> 00:32:26.000
his army, and concentrates his forces.

00:32:27.020 --> 00:32:29.480
When in difficult country, do not encamp.

00:32:30.240 --> 00:32:33.740
In country where high roads intersect, join hands with your allies.

00:32:34.440 --> 00:32:36.860
Do not linger in dangerously isolated positions.

00:32:37.760 --> 00:32:40.620
In hemmed-in situations, you must resort to stratagem.

00:32:41.100 --> 00:32:43.540
In desperate position, you must fight.

00:32:44.740 --> 00:32:49.860
There are roads which must not be followed, armies which must not be attacked, towns which

00:32:49.860 --> 00:32:55.720
must not be besieged, positions which must not be contested, commands of the sovereign

00:32:55.720 --> 00:32:57.800
which must not be obeyed.

00:32:58.640 --> 00:33:03.440
The general who thoroughly understands the advantages that accompany variation of tactics

00:33:03.440 --> 00:33:05.380
knows how to handle his troops.

00:33:05.980 --> 00:33:10.620
The general who does not understand these may be well acquainted with the configuration

00:33:10.620 --> 00:33:14.900
of the country, yet he will not be able to turn his knowledge to practical account.

00:33:15.700 --> 00:33:21.680
So the student of war who is unversed in the art of war of varying his plans, even though

00:33:21.680 --> 00:33:26.320
he be acquainted with the five advantages, will fail to make the best use of his men.

00:33:27.160 --> 00:33:32.400
Hence in the wise leader's plans, considerations of advantage and of disadvantage will be blended

00:33:32.400 --> 00:33:32.980
together.

00:33:33.720 --> 00:33:39.200
If our expectation of advantage be tempered in this way, we may succeed in accomplishing

00:33:39.200 --> 00:33:40.960
the essential part of our schemes.

00:33:41.980 --> 00:33:47.060
If on the other hand, in the midst of difficulties we are always ready to seize an advantage,

00:33:47.580 --> 00:33:49.840
we may extricate ourselves from misfortune.

00:33:51.700 --> 00:33:56.780
Reduce the hostile chiefs by inflicting damage on them, and make trouble for them, and keep

00:33:56.780 --> 00:33:58.320
them constantly engaged.

00:33:58.960 --> 00:34:02.760
Hold out specious allurements and make them rush to any given point.

00:34:04.060 --> 00:34:09.200
The art of war teaches us to rely not on the likelihood of the enemy's not coming, but

00:34:09.200 --> 00:34:11.280
on our own readiness to receive him.

00:34:11.760 --> 00:34:16.900
Not on the chance of his not attacking, but rather on the fact that we have made our position

00:34:16.900 --> 00:34:17.660
unassailable.

00:34:18.900 --> 00:34:21.880
There are five dangerous faults which may affect a general.

00:34:23.180 --> 00:34:25.780
One, recklessness which leads to destruction.

00:34:26.820 --> 00:34:29.120
Two, cowardice which leads to capture.

00:34:29.900 --> 00:34:33.940
Three, a hasty temper which can be provoked by insults.

00:34:34.060 --> 00:34:37.260
Four, a delicacy of honor which is sensitive to shame.

00:34:38.100 --> 00:34:42.460
Five, over-solicitude for his men which exposes him to worry and trouble.

00:34:43.700 --> 00:34:48.360
These are the five besetting sins of a general, ruinous to the conduct of war.

00:34:49.340 --> 00:34:54.260
When an army is overthrown and its leader slain, the cause will surely be found among

00:34:54.260 --> 00:34:55.760
these five dangerous faults.

00:34:56.440 --> 00:34:58.580
Let them be a subject of meditation.

00:35:24.340 --> 00:35:27.640
Part IX. The Army on the March.

00:35:27.640 --> 00:35:29.860
Sun Tzu said,

00:35:57.640 --> 00:36:04.960
Do not advance to meet it in midstream. It will be best to let half the army get across, and then deliver your attack.

00:36:06.200 --> 00:36:11.820
If you are anxious to fight, you should not go to meet the invader near a river which he has to cross.

00:36:12.880 --> 00:36:21.440
Mour your craft higher up than the enemy, and facing the sun. Do not move upstream to meet the enemy. So much for river warfare.

00:36:22.360 --> 00:36:28.380
In crossing salt marshes, your sole concern should be to get over them quickly, without any delay.

00:36:29.640 --> 00:36:39.940
If forced to fight in a salt marsh, you should have water and grass near you and get your back to a clump of trees. So much for operations in salt marshes.

00:36:39.940 --> 00:36:51.060
In dry, level country, take up an easily accessible position with rising ground to your right and on your rear, so that the danger may be in front and safety lie behind.

00:36:52.080 --> 00:36:54.500
So much for campaigning in flat country.

00:36:55.820 --> 00:37:02.940
These are the four useful branches of military knowledge which enabled the Yellow Emperor to vanquish four several sovereigns.

00:37:03.680 --> 00:37:07.940
All armies prefer high ground to low, and sunny places to dark.

00:37:07.940 --> 00:37:16.440
If you are careful of your men and camp on hard ground, the army will be free from disease of every kind, and this will spell victory.

00:37:17.640 --> 00:37:22.780
When you come to a hill or a bank, occupy the sunny side, with the slope on your right rear.

00:37:23.660 --> 00:37:30.300
Thus you will at once act for the benefit of your soldiers, and utilize the natural advantages of the ground.

00:37:31.140 --> 00:37:41.500
When, in consequence of heavy rains up country, a river which you wish to ford is swollen and flecked with foam, you must wait until it subsides.

00:37:42.120 --> 00:37:56.020
Country in which there are precipitous cliffs with torrents running between, deep natural hollows, confined places, tangled thickets, quagmires and crevasses, should be left with all possible speed and not approached.

00:37:57.140 --> 00:38:01.420
While we keep away from such places, we should get the enemy to approach them.

00:38:01.600 --> 00:38:04.920
While we face them, we should let the enemy have them on his rear.

00:38:06.440 --> 00:38:16.760
If in the neighborhood of your camp there should be any hilly country, ponds surrounded by aquatic grass, hollow basins filled with reeds, or woods with thick undergrowth,

00:38:17.380 --> 00:38:24.800
they must be carefully routed out and searched, for these are places where men in ambush or insidious spies are likely to be lurking.

00:38:25.820 --> 00:38:31.940
When the enemy is close at hand and remains quiet, he is relying on the natural strength of his position.

00:38:32.860 --> 00:38:37.800
When he keeps aloof and tries to provoke a battle, he is anxious for the other side to advance.

00:38:39.180 --> 00:38:43.080
If his place of encampment is easy of access, he is tendering a bait.

00:38:44.420 --> 00:38:48.120
Movement amongst the trees of a forest shows that the enemy is advancing.

00:38:49.060 --> 00:38:55.360
The appearance of a number of screens in the midst of thick grass means that the enemy wants to make us suspicious.

00:38:57.180 --> 00:39:00.520
The rising of birds in their flight is the sign of an ambuscade.

00:39:01.220 --> 00:39:04.140
Startled beasts indicate that a sudden attack is coming.

00:39:05.700 --> 00:39:10.660
When there is dust rising in a high column, it is the sign of chariots advancing.

00:39:11.620 --> 00:39:16.760
When the dust is low, but spread over a wide area, it betokens the approach of infantry.

00:39:16.760 --> 00:39:22.820
When it branches out in different directions, it shows that parties have been sent to collect firewood.

00:39:23.720 --> 00:39:29.260
A few clouds of dust moving to and fro signify that the army is encamping.

00:39:29.640 --> 00:39:34.300
Humble words and increased preparations are signs that the enemy is about to advance.

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:39.980
Violent language and driving forward as if to the attack are signs that he will retreat.

00:39:41.140 --> 00:39:44.840
When the light chariots come out first and take up a position on the wings,

00:39:44.840 --> 00:39:48.020
it is a sign that the enemy is forming for battle.

00:39:49.220 --> 00:39:53.300
Peace proposals unaccompanied by a sworn covenant indicate a plot.

00:39:54.880 --> 00:40:00.600
When there is much running about and the soldiers fall into rank, it means that the critical moment has come.

00:40:01.540 --> 00:40:05.340
When some are seen advancing and some retreating, it is a lure.

00:40:06.660 --> 00:40:10.520
When the soldiers stand leaning on their spears, they are faint from want of food.

00:40:10.520 --> 00:40:16.500
If those who are sent to draw water begin by drinking themselves, the army is suffering from thirst.

00:40:17.580 --> 00:40:23.140
If the enemy sees an advantage to be gained and makes no effort to secure it, the soldiers are exhausted.

00:40:24.160 --> 00:40:27.760
If birds gather on any spot, it is unoccupied.

00:40:28.180 --> 00:40:30.420
Clamor by night betokens nervousness.

00:40:31.900 --> 00:40:35.460
If there is a disturbance in the camp, the general's authority is weak.

00:40:36.080 --> 00:40:40.280
If the banners and flags are shifted about, sedition is afoot.

00:40:40.880 --> 00:40:44.640
If the officers are angry, it means that the men are weary.

00:40:46.400 --> 00:40:50.460
When an army feeds its horses with grain and kills its cattle for food,

00:40:50.860 --> 00:40:56.240
and when the men do not hang their cooking pots over the campfires showing that they will not return to their tents,

00:40:57.000 --> 00:40:59.920
you may know that they are determined to fight to the death.

00:41:01.040 --> 00:41:09.560
The sight of men whispering together in small knots or speaking in subdued tones points to disaffection amongst the rank and file.

00:41:10.840 --> 00:41:14.560
Too frequent rewards signify that the enemy is at the end of his resources.

00:41:15.300 --> 00:41:18.660
Too many punishments betray a condition of dire distress.

00:41:20.160 --> 00:41:26.620
To begin by bluster, but afterwards to take fright at the enemy's numbers, shows a supreme lack of intelligence.

00:41:27.640 --> 00:41:33.580
When envoys are sent with compliments in their mouths, it is a sign that the enemy wishes for a truce.

00:41:34.700 --> 00:41:43.020
If the enemy's troops march up angrily and remain facing ours for a long time without either joining battle or taking themselves off again,

00:41:43.500 --> 00:41:47.260
the situation is one that demands great vigilance and circumspection.

00:41:48.340 --> 00:41:52.660
If our troops are no more in number than the enemy, that is amply sufficient.

00:41:52.920 --> 00:41:55.460
It only means that no direct attack can be made.

00:41:55.460 --> 00:42:03.760
What we can do is simply to concentrate all our available strength, keep a close watch on the enemy, and obtain reinforcements.

00:42:04.840 --> 00:42:10.820
He who exercises no forethought but makes light of his opponents is sure to be captured by them.

00:42:12.020 --> 00:42:17.360
If soldiers are punished before they have grown attached to you, they will not prove submissive.

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:21.260
And, unless submissive, they will be practically useless.

00:42:22.100 --> 00:42:28.740
If, when the soldiers have become attached to you, punishments are not enforced, they will still be useless.

00:42:30.060 --> 00:42:37.020
Therefore, soldiers must be treated in the first instance with humanity, but kept under control by means of iron discipline.

00:42:37.780 --> 00:42:39.860
This is a certain road to victory.

00:42:41.340 --> 00:42:46.460
If, in training soldiers, commands are habitually enforced, the army will be well disciplined.

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:49.500
If not, its discipline will be bad.

00:42:49.500 --> 00:42:57.260
If a general shows confidence in his men, but always insists on his orders being obeyed, the gain will be mutual.

00:43:04.420 --> 00:43:08.740
Sun Tzu said, we may distinguish six kinds of terrain.

00:43:08.740 --> 00:43:26.180
To wit, one, accessible ground, two, entangling ground, three, temporizing ground, four, narrow passes, five, precipitous heights, six, positions at a great distance from the enemy.

00:43:27.340 --> 00:43:31.020
Ground which can be freely traversed by both sides is called accessible.

00:43:31.640 --> 00:43:40.080
With regard to ground of this nature, be before the enemy in occupying the raised and sunny spots, and carefully guard your line of supplies.

00:43:40.980 --> 00:43:43.500
Then you will be able to fight with advantage.

00:43:44.600 --> 00:43:49.180
Ground which can be abandoned but is hard to re-occupy is called entangling.

00:43:50.260 --> 00:43:55.500
From a position of this sort, if the enemy is unprepared, you may sally forth and defeat him.

00:43:55.500 --> 00:44:04.480
But if the enemy is prepared for your coming and you fail to defeat him, then, return being impossible, disaster will ensue.

00:44:05.300 --> 00:44:11.180
When the position is such that neither side will gain by making the first move, it is called temporizing ground.

00:44:12.380 --> 00:44:23.380
In a position of this sort, even though the enemy should offer us an attractive bait, it will be advisable not to stir forth, but rather to retreat, thus enticing the enemy in his turn.

00:44:24.300 --> 00:44:29.140
Then, when part of his army has come out, we may deliver our attack with advantage.

00:44:30.860 --> 00:44:38.400
With regard to narrow passes, if you can occupy them first, let them be strongly garrisoned and await the advent of the enemy.

00:44:39.280 --> 00:44:47.360
Should the army forestall you in occupying a pass, do not go after him if the pass is fully garrisoned, but only if it is weakly garrisoned.

00:44:47.920 --> 00:44:56.920
With regard to precipitous heights, if you are beforehand with your adversary, you should occupy the raised and sunny spots and there wait for him to come up.

00:44:58.280 --> 00:45:05.000
If the enemy has occupied them before you, do not follow him, but retreat and try to entice him away.

00:45:06.680 --> 00:45:16.260
If you are situated at a great distance from the enemy and the strength of the two armies is equal, it is not easy to provoke a battle and fighting will be to your disadvantage.

00:45:17.100 --> 00:45:25.200
These six are the principles connected with Earth. The general who has attained a responsible post must be careful to study them.

00:45:26.140 --> 00:45:34.400
Now, an army is exposed to six several calamities, not arising from natural causes, but from faults for which the general is responsible.

00:45:34.400 --> 00:45:48.760
These are 1. Flight, 2. Insubordination, 3. Collapse, 4. Ruin, 5. Disorganization, 6. Route.

00:45:50.460 --> 00:45:58.140
Other conditions being equal, if one force is hurled against another ten times its size, the result will be the flight of the former.

00:45:58.140 --> 00:46:04.920
When the common soldiers are too strong and their officers too weak, the result is insubordination.

00:46:05.640 --> 00:46:10.780
When the officers are too strong and the common soldiers too weak, the result is collapse.

00:46:12.080 --> 00:46:19.140
When the higher officers are angry and insubordinate and on meeting the enemy give battle on their own account from a feeling of resentment,

00:46:19.960 --> 00:46:25.520
before the commander-in-chief can tell whether or not he is in a position to fight, the result is ruin.

00:46:26.620 --> 00:46:32.260
When the general is weak and without authority, when his orders are not clear and distinct,

00:46:32.820 --> 00:46:42.500
when there are no fixed duties assigned to officers and men, and the ranks are formed in a slovenly haphazard manner, the result is utter disorganization.

00:46:43.940 --> 00:46:50.460
When a general, unable to estimate the enemy's strength, allows an inferior force to engage a larger one,

00:46:50.460 --> 00:46:58.600
or hurls a weak detachment against a powerful one, and neglects to place picked soldiers in the front rank, the result must be route.

00:47:00.320 --> 00:47:06.760
These are six ways of courting defeat which must be carefully noted by the general who has attained a responsible post.

00:47:07.960 --> 00:47:13.920
The natural formation of the country is the soldier's best ally, but a power of estimating the adversary,

00:47:13.920 --> 00:47:23.040
of controlling the forces of victory, and of shrewdly calculating difficulties, dangers, and distances, constitutes the test of a great general.

00:47:24.080 --> 00:47:29.360
He who knows these things and in fighting puts his knowledge into practice will win his battles.

00:47:30.180 --> 00:47:34.200
He who knows them not, nor practices them, will surely be defeated.

00:47:35.260 --> 00:47:40.680
If fighting is sure to result in victory, then you must fight, even though the ruler forbid it.

00:47:40.680 --> 00:47:46.200
If fighting will not result in victory, then you must not fight, even at the ruler's bidding.

00:47:47.580 --> 00:47:52.660
The general who advances without coveting fame and retreats without fearing disgrace,

00:47:53.180 --> 00:47:59.600
whose only thought is to protect his country and do good service for his sovereign, is the jewel of the kingdom.

00:48:01.380 --> 00:48:05.900
Regard your soldiers as your children, and they will follow you into the deepest valleys.

00:48:05.900 --> 00:48:11.720
Look upon them as your own beloved sons, and they will stand by you even unto death.

00:48:12.980 --> 00:48:20.640
If, however, you are indulgent, but unable to make your authority felt, kind-hearted, but unable to enforce your commands,

00:48:21.200 --> 00:48:27.000
and incapable, moreover, of quelling disorder, then your soldiers must be likened to spoilt children.

00:48:27.580 --> 00:48:30.060
They are useless for any practical purpose.

00:48:31.380 --> 00:48:37.860
If we know that our own men are in a condition to attack but are unaware that the enemy is not open to attack,

00:48:38.140 --> 00:48:40.940
we have gone only halfway towards victory.

00:48:42.160 --> 00:48:48.500
If we know that the enemy is open to attack but are unaware that our own men are not in a condition to attack,

00:48:48.900 --> 00:48:51.600
we have gone only halfway towards victory.

00:48:52.880 --> 00:48:59.100
If we know that the enemy is open to attack and also know that our men are in a condition to attack,

00:48:59.100 --> 00:49:07.140
But are unaware that the nature of the ground makes fighting impracticable, we have still only gone halfway towards victory.

00:49:08.180 --> 00:49:15.940
Hence the experienced soldier, once in motion, is never bewildered. Once he has broken camp, he is never at a loss.

00:49:16.760 --> 00:49:22.760
Hence the saying, If you know the enemy and know yourself, your victory will not stand in doubt.

00:49:22.760 --> 00:49:28.340
If you know heaven and know earth, you may make your victory complete.

00:49:53.820 --> 00:49:58.060
XI. THE NINE SITUATIONS.

00:49:58.060 --> 00:50:02.940
Sun Tzu said, The art of war recognizes nine varieties of ground.

00:50:04.020 --> 00:50:05.760
One, dispersive ground.

00:50:06.360 --> 00:50:08.180
Two, facile ground.

00:50:08.820 --> 00:50:10.680
Three, contentious ground.

00:50:11.460 --> 00:50:13.240
Four, open ground.

00:50:13.980 --> 00:50:16.800
Five, ground of intersecting highways.

00:50:17.760 --> 00:50:19.860
Six, serious ground.

00:50:20.640 --> 00:50:22.760
Seven, difficult ground.

00:50:23.340 --> 00:50:25.760
Eight, hemmed-in ground.

00:50:25.760 --> 00:50:28.860
Nine, desperate ground.

00:50:30.380 --> 00:50:34.560
When a chieftain is fighting in his own territory, it is dispersive ground.

00:50:35.440 --> 00:50:41.220
When he is penetrated into hostile territory, but to no great distance, it is facile ground.

00:50:42.480 --> 00:50:48.120
Ground of the possession of which imports great advantage to either side is contentious ground.

00:50:49.360 --> 00:50:53.320
Ground on which each side has liberty of movement is open ground.

00:50:54.540 --> 00:51:04.780
Ground which forms the key to three contiguous states so that he who occupies it first has most of the empire at his command is a ground of intersecting highways.

00:51:06.140 --> 00:51:13.920
When an army has penetrated into the heart of a hostile country, leaving a number of fortified cities in its rear, it is serious ground.

00:51:15.180 --> 00:51:23.820
Mountain forests, rugged steeps, marshes and fens, all country that is hard to traverse, this is difficult ground.

00:51:25.020 --> 00:51:37.560
Ground which is reached through narrow gorges and from which we can only retire by tortuous paths so that a small number of the enemy would suffice to crush a large body of our men, this is hemmed-in ground.

00:51:37.560 --> 00:51:44.320
Ground on which we can only be saved from destruction by fighting without delay is desperate ground.

00:51:45.560 --> 00:51:54.360
On dispersive ground, therefore, fight not. On facile ground, halt not. On contentious ground, attack not.

00:51:55.580 --> 00:52:03.080
On open ground, do not try to block the enemy's way. On the ground of intersecting highways, join hands with your allies.

00:52:03.900 --> 00:52:10.620
On serious ground, gather and plunder. In difficult ground, keep steadily on the march.

00:52:11.880 --> 00:52:17.860
On hemmed-in ground, resort to stratagem. On desperate ground, fight.

00:52:19.520 --> 00:52:36.040
Those who were called skillful leaders of old knew how to drive a wedge between the enemy's front and rear, to prevent cooperation between his large and small divisions, to hinder the good troops from rescuing the bad, the officers from rallying their men.

00:52:36.740 --> 00:52:47.100
When the enemy's men were united, they managed to keep them in disorder. When it was to their advantage, they made a forward move. When otherwise, they stopped still.

00:52:48.540 --> 00:53:01.980
If asked how to cope with a great host of the enemy in orderly array, and on the point of marching to the attack, I should say, begin by seizing something which your opponent holds dear. Then he will be amenable to your will.

00:53:03.460 --> 00:53:12.620
Rapidity is the essence of war. Take advantage of the enemy's unreadiness. Make your way by unexpected routes, and attack unguarded spots.

00:53:13.780 --> 00:53:26.200
The following are the principles to be observed by an invading force. The further you penetrate into a country, the greater will be the solidarity of your troops, and thus the defenders will not prevail against you.

00:53:26.200 --> 00:53:31.200
Make forays in fertile country in order to supply your army with food.

00:53:32.080 --> 00:53:36.160
Carefully study the well-being of your men, and do not overtax them.

00:53:36.740 --> 00:53:39.280
Concentrate your energy and hoard your strength.

00:53:40.520 --> 00:53:45.440
Keep your army continually on the move, and devise unfathomable plans.

00:53:46.300 --> 00:53:56.600
Throw your soldiers into positions whence there is no escape, and they will prefer death to flight. If they will face death, there is nothing they may not achieve.

00:53:57.560 --> 00:54:00.880
Officers and men alike will put forth their uttermost strength.

00:54:02.040 --> 00:54:14.160
Soldiers, when in desperate straits, lose the sense of fear. If there is no place of refuge, they will stand firm. If they are in hostile country, they will show a stubborn front.

00:54:14.860 --> 00:54:18.140
If there is no help for it, they will fight hard.

00:54:19.200 --> 00:54:23.980
Thus, without waiting to be marshaled, the soldiers will be constantly on the quivive.

00:54:24.600 --> 00:54:27.120
Without waiting to be asked, they will do your will.

00:54:27.740 --> 00:54:29.880
Without restrictions, they will be faithful.

00:54:30.640 --> 00:54:32.960
Without giving orders, they can be trusted.

00:54:34.820 --> 00:54:38.380
Prohibit the taking of omens, and do away with superstitious doubts.

00:54:39.100 --> 00:54:43.440
Then, until death itself comes, no calamity need be feared.

00:54:44.700 --> 00:54:49.920
If our soldiers are not overburdened with money, it is not because they have a distaste for riches.

00:54:50.660 --> 00:54:55.700
If their lives are not unduly long, it is not because they are disinclined to longevity.

00:54:56.980 --> 00:55:06.900
On the day they are ordered out to battle, your soldiers may weep, those sitting up bedewing their garments, and those lying down, letting the tears run down their cheeks.

00:55:07.440 --> 00:55:12.900
But let them once be brought to bay, and they will display the courage of a Chu, or a Kuih.

00:55:14.440 --> 00:55:17.700
The skillful tactician may be likened to the Shuai Zhan.

00:55:18.740 --> 00:55:22.900
Now, the Shuai Zhan is a snake that is found in the Chiung Mountains.

00:55:23.640 --> 00:55:26.460
Strike at its head, and you will be attacked by its tail.

00:55:27.120 --> 00:55:30.100
Strike at its tail, and you will be attacked by its head.

00:55:30.680 --> 00:55:34.280
Strike at the middle, and you will be attacked by head and tail both.

00:55:35.680 --> 00:55:40.500
Asked if an army can be made to imitate the Shuai Zhan, I should answer, yes.

00:55:41.120 --> 00:55:48.300
For the men of Wu and the men of Yue are enemies, yet if they are crossing a river in the same boat and are caught by a storm,

00:55:48.800 --> 00:55:52.840
they will come to each other's assistance just as the left hand helps the right.

00:55:54.120 --> 00:55:59.840
Hence, it is not enough to put one's trust in the tethering of horses and the burying of chariot wheels in the ground.

00:56:00.460 --> 00:56:06.760
The principle on which to manage an army is to set up one standard of courage, which all must reach.

00:56:07.760 --> 00:56:13.280
How to make the best of both strong and weak, that is a question involving the proper use of ground.

00:56:14.360 --> 00:56:21.260
Thus, the skillful general conducts his army just as though he were leading a single man willy-nilly by the hand.

00:56:22.360 --> 00:56:26.620
It is the business of a general to be quiet and thus ensure secrecy,

00:56:26.620 --> 00:56:30.140
upright and just, and thus maintain order.

00:56:31.100 --> 00:56:38.440
He must be able to mystify his officers and men by false reports and appearances, and thus keep them in total ignorance.

00:56:40.080 --> 00:56:45.220
By altering his arrangements and changing his plans, he keeps the enemy without definite knowledge.

00:56:45.920 --> 00:56:51.820
By shifting his camp and taking circuitous routes, he prevents the enemy from anticipating his purpose.

00:56:52.660 --> 00:57:00.220
At the critical moment, the leader of an army acts like one who has climbed up a height and then kicks away the ladder behind him.

00:57:01.140 --> 00:57:05.380
He carries his men deep into hostile territory before he shows his hand.

00:57:06.620 --> 00:57:11.500
He burns his boats and breaks his cooking pots, like a shepherd driving a flock of sheep.

00:57:11.800 --> 00:57:16.400
He drives his men this way and that, and nothing knows whether he is going.

00:57:17.280 --> 00:57:22.500
To muster his host and bring it into danger, this may be termed the business of the general.

00:57:23.720 --> 00:57:30.040
The different measures suited to the nine varieties of ground, the expediency of aggressive or defensive tactics,

00:57:30.620 --> 00:57:35.940
and the fundamental laws of human nature, these are things that must most certainly be studied.

00:57:37.120 --> 00:57:43.060
When invading hostile territory, the general principle is that penetrating deeply brings cohesion.

00:57:43.060 --> 00:57:46.080
Penetrating but a short way means dispersion.

00:57:47.220 --> 00:57:54.200
When you leave your own country behind and take your army across neighborhood territory, you find yourself on critical ground.

00:57:55.060 --> 00:57:59.980
When there are means of communication on all four sides, the ground is one of intersecting highways.

00:58:01.300 --> 00:58:05.040
When you penetrate deeply into a country, it is serious ground.

00:58:05.680 --> 00:58:09.000
When you penetrate but a little way, it is facile ground.

00:58:10.020 --> 00:58:16.460
When you have the enemy's strongholds on your rear and narrow passes in front, it is hemmed-in ground.

00:58:17.220 --> 00:58:21.300
When there is no place of refuge at all, it is desperate ground.

00:58:22.820 --> 00:58:27.380
Therefore, on dispersive ground, I would inspire my men with unity of purpose.

00:58:28.000 --> 00:58:32.960
On facile ground, I would see that there is close connection between all parts of my army.

00:58:33.800 --> 00:58:36.540
On contentious ground, I would hurry out my rear.

00:58:37.160 --> 00:58:41.380
On open ground, I would keep a vigilant eye on my defenses.

00:58:42.380 --> 00:58:45.900
On ground of intersecting highways, I would consolidate my alliances.

00:58:47.260 --> 00:58:51.320
On serious ground, I would try to ensure a continuous stream of supplies.

00:58:52.200 --> 00:58:55.720
On difficult ground, I would keep pushing on along the road.

00:58:57.000 --> 00:59:00.340
On hemmed-in ground, I would block any way of retreat.

00:59:00.340 --> 00:59:06.760
On desperate ground, I would proclaim to my soldiers the hopelessness of saving their lives.

00:59:07.840 --> 00:59:12.120
For it is the soldier's disposition to offer an obstinate resistance when surrounded,

00:59:12.580 --> 00:59:17.840
to fight hard when he cannot help himself, and to obey promptly when he has fallen into danger.

00:59:18.720 --> 00:59:24.200
We cannot enter into alliance with neighboring princes until we are acquainted with their designs.

00:59:24.880 --> 00:59:29.960
We are not fit to lead an army on the march unless we are familiar with the face of the country.

00:59:29.960 --> 00:59:36.020
Its mountains and forests, its pitfalls and precipices, its marshes and swamps.

00:59:36.740 --> 00:59:42.360
We shall be unable to turn natural advantages to account unless we make use of local guides.

00:59:43.940 --> 00:59:50.120
To be ignored of any one of the following four or five principles does not befit a warlike prince.

00:59:51.640 --> 00:59:56.460
When a warlike prince attacks a powerful state, his generalship shows itself

00:59:56.460 --> 00:59:59.340
in preventing the concentration of the enemy's forces.

01:00:00.120 --> 01:00:05.300
He over-aws his opponents, and their allies are prevented from joining against him.

01:00:06.440 --> 01:00:12.960
Hence, he does not strive to ally himself with all and sundry, nor does he foster the power of other states.

01:00:13.800 --> 01:00:18.980
He carries out his own secret designs, keeping his antagonists in awe.

01:00:19.800 --> 01:00:24.000
Thus, he is able to capture their cities and overthrow their kingdoms.

01:00:25.780 --> 01:00:31.180
Bestow rewards without regard to rule, issue orders without regard to previous arrangements,

01:00:31.640 --> 01:00:36.780
and you will be able to handle a whole army as though you had to do with but a single man.

01:00:38.100 --> 01:00:42.320
Confront your soldiers with the deed itself. Never let them know your design.

01:00:43.180 --> 01:00:49.560
When the outlook is bright, bring it before their eyes, but tell them nothing when the situation is gloomy.

01:00:50.440 --> 01:00:58.400
Place your army in deadly peril and it will survive. Plunge it into desperate straits and it will come off in safety.

01:00:59.340 --> 01:01:05.700
For it is precisely when a force has fallen into harm's way that it is capable of striking a blow for victory.

01:01:07.360 --> 01:01:12.480
Success in warfare is gained by carefully accommodating ourselves to the enemy's purpose.

01:01:12.480 --> 01:01:19.600
By persistently hanging on the enemy's flank, we shall succeed in the long run in killing the commander-in-chief.

01:01:20.300 --> 01:01:23.940
This is called ability to accomplish a thing by sheer cunning.

01:01:25.660 --> 01:01:34.380
On the day that you take up your command, block the frontier passes, destroy the official tallies, and stop the passage of all emissaries.

01:01:35.080 --> 01:01:38.840
Be stern in the council chamber so that you may control the situation.

01:01:38.840 --> 01:01:43.840
If the enemy leaves a door open, you must rush in.

01:01:44.520 --> 01:01:50.480
Forstall your opponent by seizing what he holds dear and subtly contrive to time his arrival on the ground.

01:01:51.560 --> 01:01:58.440
Walk in the path defined by rule and accommodate yourself to the enemy until you can fight a decisive battle.

01:01:59.620 --> 01:02:04.520
At first, then, exhibit the coyness of a maiden until the enemy gives you an opening.

01:02:05.440 --> 01:02:11.520
Afterwards, emulate the rapidity of a running hare, and it will be too late for the enemy to oppose you.

01:02:35.820 --> 01:02:36.740
XII.

01:02:37.040 --> 01:02:39.100
The Attack by Fire.

01:02:39.700 --> 01:02:40.860
Sun Tzu said,

01:02:41.320 --> 01:02:43.620
There are five ways of attacking with fire.

01:02:44.480 --> 01:02:46.920
The first is to burn soldiers in their camp.

01:02:47.520 --> 01:02:49.080
The second is to burn stores.

01:02:49.860 --> 01:02:51.900
The third is to burn baggage trains.

01:02:52.840 --> 01:02:55.320
The fourth is to burn arsenals and magazines.

01:02:56.160 --> 01:02:59.640
The fifth is to hurl dropping fire amongst the enemy.

01:03:00.940 --> 01:03:04.520
In order to carry out an attack, we must have means available.

01:03:05.240 --> 01:03:08.880
The material for raising fire should always be kept in readiness.

01:03:10.380 --> 01:03:12.980
There is a proper season for making attacks with fire,

01:03:13.280 --> 01:03:15.580
and special days for starting a conflagration.

01:03:17.120 --> 01:03:19.640
The proper season is when the weather is very dry.

01:03:20.340 --> 01:03:24.020
The special days are those when the moon is in the constellations of

01:03:24.020 --> 01:03:28.060
the sieve, the wall, the wing, or the crossbar,

01:03:28.540 --> 01:03:31.240
for these four are all days of rising wind.

01:03:32.560 --> 01:03:37.620
In attacking with fire, one should be prepared to meet five possible developments.

01:03:38.440 --> 01:03:42.040
1. When fire breaks out inside to enemy's camp,

01:03:42.580 --> 01:03:44.600
respond at once with an attack from without.

01:03:45.900 --> 01:03:50.180
2. If there is an outbreak of fire but the enemy's soldiers remain quiet,

01:03:50.680 --> 01:03:52.600
bide your time and do not attack.

01:03:53.820 --> 01:03:56.800
3. When the force of the flames has reached its height,

01:03:57.280 --> 01:03:59.880
follow it up with an attack if that is practicable.

01:03:59.880 --> 01:04:02.150
If not, stay where you are.

01:04:03.580 --> 01:04:07.260
4. If it is possible to make an assault with fire from without,

01:04:07.760 --> 01:04:12.440
do not wait for it to break out within, but deliver your attack at a favourable moment.

01:04:13.900 --> 01:04:17.640
5. When you start a fire, be to windward of it.

01:04:17.960 --> 01:04:19.660
Do not attack from the leeward.

01:04:21.400 --> 01:04:26.080
A wind that rises in the daytime lasts long, but a night breeze soon falls.

01:04:26.840 --> 01:04:30.940
In every army, the five developments connected with fire must be known,

01:04:31.400 --> 01:04:35.640
the movements of the stars calculated, and a watch kept for the proper days.

01:04:36.700 --> 01:04:40.780
Hence, those who use fire as an aid to the attack show intelligence.

01:04:41.420 --> 01:04:45.800
Those who use water as an aid to the attack gain an accession of strength.

01:04:46.980 --> 01:04:51.620
By means of water, an enemy may be intercepted, but not robbed of all his belongings.

01:04:52.780 --> 01:04:56.960
Unhappy is the fate of one who tries to win his battles and succeed in his attacks

01:04:56.960 --> 01:05:03.380
without cultivating the spirit of enterprise, for the result is a waste of time and general stagnation.

01:05:04.860 --> 01:05:08.540
Hence the saying, the enlightened ruler lays his plans well ahead.

01:05:09.240 --> 01:05:11.500
The good general cultivates his resources.

01:05:13.060 --> 01:05:15.380
Move not unless you see an advantage.

01:05:16.000 --> 01:05:18.880
Use not your troops unless there is something to be gained.

01:05:19.440 --> 01:05:22.060
Fight not unless the position is critical.

01:05:23.240 --> 01:05:27.300
No ruler should put troops into the field merely to gratify his own spleen.

01:05:28.100 --> 01:05:30.680
No general should fight a battle simply out of peak.

01:05:31.980 --> 01:05:34.520
If it is to your advantage, make a forward move.

01:05:34.960 --> 01:05:37.080
If not, stay where you are.

01:05:39.400 --> 01:05:41.440
Anger may in time change to gladness.

01:05:42.360 --> 01:05:44.480
Vexation may be succeeded by content.

01:05:45.120 --> 01:05:49.760
But a kingdom that has once been destroyed can never come again into being,

01:05:50.200 --> 01:05:52.840
nor can the dead ever be brought back to life.

01:05:53.520 --> 01:05:57.740
Hence the enlightened ruler is heedful and the good general full of caution.

01:05:58.560 --> 01:06:02.000
This is the way to keep a country at peace and an army intact.

01:06:06.300 --> 01:06:09.200
Part 13 The Use of Spies

01:06:10.240 --> 01:06:11.680
Sun Tzu said,

01:06:44.460 --> 01:06:48.800
This being so, to remain in ignorance of the enemy's conditions,

01:06:48.860 --> 01:06:52.460
simply because one grudges the outlay of a hundred ounces of silver

01:06:52.460 --> 01:06:56.400
in honors and emoluments, is the height of inhumanity.

01:06:57.880 --> 01:07:04.260
One who acts thus is no leader of men, no present help to his sovereign, no master of victory.

01:07:05.220 --> 01:07:09.780
Thus what enables the wise sovereign and the good general to strike and conquer

01:07:09.780 --> 01:07:13.860
and achieve things beyond the reach of ordinary men is foreknowledge.

01:07:15.320 --> 01:07:18.400
Now this foreknowledge cannot be elicited from spirits.

01:07:19.000 --> 01:07:24.080
It cannot be obtained inductively from experience, nor by any deductive calculation.

01:07:25.360 --> 01:07:29.280
Knowledge of the enemy's dispositions can only be obtained from other men.

01:07:30.300 --> 01:07:34.480
Hence the use of spies, of whom there are five classes.

01:07:47.720 --> 01:07:53.200
When these five kinds of spy are all at work, none can discover the secret system.

01:07:53.960 --> 01:07:56.840
This is called divine manipulation of the threads.

01:07:57.520 --> 01:08:00.280
It is the sovereign's most precious faculty.

01:08:01.600 --> 01:08:05.760
Having local spies means employing the services of the inhabitants of a district.

01:08:06.520 --> 01:08:10.080
Having inward spies, making use of officials of the enemy.

01:08:11.040 --> 01:08:16.800
Having converted spies, getting hold of the enemy's spies and using them for our own purposes.

01:08:18.020 --> 01:08:22.620
Having doomed spies, doing certain things openly for purposes of deception,

01:08:23.180 --> 01:08:26.380
and allowing our spies to know of them and report them to the enemy.

01:08:28.000 --> 01:08:32.300
Surviving spies, finally, are those who bring back news from the enemy's camp.

01:08:33.740 --> 01:08:38.540
Hence it is that which, none in the whole army are more intimate relations to be maintained

01:08:38.540 --> 01:08:39.840
than with spies.

01:08:40.740 --> 01:08:42.600
None should be more liberally rewarded,

01:08:43.320 --> 01:08:46.340
and no other business should greater secrecy be preserved.

01:08:47.480 --> 01:08:51.440
Spies cannot be usefully employed without a certain intuitive sagacity.

01:08:52.260 --> 01:08:56.000
They cannot be properly managed without benevolence and straightforwardness.

01:08:56.840 --> 01:09:02.060
Without subtle ingenuity of mind, one cannot make certain of the truth of their reports.

01:09:02.760 --> 01:09:07.560
Be subtle, be subtle, and use your spies for every kind of business.

01:09:08.600 --> 01:09:12.440
If a secret piece of news is divulged by a spy before the time is ripe,

01:09:12.920 --> 01:09:16.380
he must be put to death together with the man to whom the secret was told.

01:09:17.340 --> 01:09:22.760
Whether the object be to crush an army, to storm a city, or to assassinate an individual,

01:09:22.760 --> 01:09:27.180
it is always necessary to begin by finding out the names of the attendants,

01:09:27.520 --> 01:09:31.420
the aides-de-camp, and doorkeepers and sentries of the general in command.

01:09:32.260 --> 01:09:34.860
Our spies must be commissioned to ascertain these.

01:09:36.040 --> 01:09:40.120
The enemy's spies who have come to spy on us must be sought out,

01:09:40.280 --> 01:09:43.540
tempted with bribes, led away, and comfortably housed.

01:09:44.200 --> 01:09:47.740
Thus they will become converted spies and available for our service.

01:09:49.000 --> 01:09:51.780
It is through the information brought by the converted spy

01:09:51.780 --> 01:09:55.620
that we are able to acquire and employ local and inward spies.

01:09:56.960 --> 01:10:01.200
It is owing to this information again that we can cause the doomed spy

01:10:01.200 --> 01:10:03.240
to carry false tidings to the enemy.

01:10:04.520 --> 01:10:09.440
Lastly, it is by this information that the surviving spy can be used on appointed occasions.

01:10:10.980 --> 01:10:15.520
The end and aim of spying in all its five varieties is knowledge of the enemy,

01:10:15.560 --> 01:10:20.700
and this knowledge can only be derived in the first instance from the converted spy.

01:10:21.340 --> 01:10:25.820
Hence it is essential that the converted spy be treated with the utmost liberality.

01:10:27.060 --> 01:10:32.820
Of old, the rise of the Yin dynasty was due to Yi Qi, who had served under the Xia.

01:10:33.700 --> 01:10:39.320
Likewise, the rise of the Chu dynasty was due to Lu Ya, who had served under the Yin.

01:10:40.960 --> 01:10:45.500
Hence, it is only the enlightened ruler and the wise general who will use the highest

01:10:45.500 --> 01:10:50.580
intelligence of the army for purposes of spying, and thereby they achieve great results.

01:10:51.260 --> 01:10:53.960
Spies are a most important element in water,

01:10:54.360 --> 01:10:57.460
because on them depends an army's ability to move.

01:10:59.380 --> 01:11:01.000
End of The Art of War

01:11:02.180 --> 01:11:08.140
